It was largely ceremonial. The author of this article should not expect nothing short of defining physical boundary disputes with Somalia to make Somaliland more independent than it already is.  Probably, he was confused for the referendum held for Identifying border with Ethiopia. His thesis sounded more like wishing pretending that there is a kind of border disputes between Somaliland and Ethiopia at the beginning and finally agreed in the end that there is no cross border dispute between us and Ethiopia.  Now it was agreed that there is no dispute with either the Ethiopian or Somalia. Since when does a better human rights record make Somaliland more independent? He can push the bar through the roof by calling Somaliland independent state that like the Ebola virus. Somaliland is nationally recognized as a sovereign state by over 35 countries.
The author’s conclusion is disappointing in that it has been entirely know that Somaliland has no border disputes with Somalia and the only dispute is with Ethiopia that it shares its border with. From the beginning he was trying to create a narrative that there are cross border disputes. It has never been the case. The author got the one he was obviously hoping for in the end.
